hands_on_practices.problem:
A gas-phase organic molecule, acetaldehyde, exhibits a well-resolved rotational–vibrational transition in the mid-Infrared (IR) at a line center wavenumber $	ilde{
u}_{0} = 1710\,\mathrm{cm}^{-1}$ at temperature $T = 296\,\mathrm{K}$. The gas pressure is $P = 0.0350\,\mathrm{atm}$. Assume the molecule’s translational velocities are distributed according to the Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution, and that the non-relativistic Doppler shift for motion along the line of sight is applicable. Ignore instrumental and natural broadening. The acetaldehyde molar mass is $M = 44.053\,\mathrm{g\,mol^{-1}}$; use the Avogadro constant $N_{A}$ and the speed of light $c$ and Boltzmann constant $k_{B}$ as fundamental constants. The collisional (pressure) broadening at $T = 296\,\mathrm{K}$ for this line is empirically characterized by a Lorentzian full width at half maximum (FWHM) per unit pressure of $C_{L} = 0.090\,\mathrm{cm^{-1}\,atm^{-1}}$.

Starting from the Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution for the line-of-sight velocity component and the non-relativistic Doppler shift, derive the Doppler full width at half maximum (FWHM) in wavenumber units, $\Delta	ilde{
u}_{D}$, for this transition. Then compute the pressure-broadened FWHM, $\Delta	ilde{
u}_{P}$, using the given $C_{L}$ and $P$, and form the dimensionless ratio $R = \Delta	ilde{
u}_{D}/\Delta	ilde{
u}_{P}$. Round your final numerical value for $R$ to four significant figures and express it as a pure number with no units.
